Storyline:
In 2001, corporate bandit Gordon Gecko finishes a jail sentence for tax evasion. Nobody is there to meet him. Bounce seven years: Gecko is advancing his book, his offended girl Winnie is a political meddler drawn in to Jake Moore, a superstar Wall Street broker, and an old foe of Gecko’s, Bretton James, eats up the firm Jake works for. At the point when Jake’s guide ends his life, Jake needs vengeance and Gordon might be the ideal partner. With the financial emergency of September 2008 as foundation, can Jake keep up Winnie’s affection, agent a rapprochement with her dad, get his vengeance, and discover assets for an environmentally friendly power energy venture he champions; or will voracity trump all? 
Money Street: Money Never Sleeps (otherwise called Wall Street 2 or Wall Street 2: Money Never Sleeps) is a 2010 American dramatization movie coordinated by Oliver Stone, a spin-off of Wall Street (1987). It stars Michael Douglas, Shia LaBeouf, Josh Brolin, Carey Mulligan, Frank Langella, Susan Sarandon and Eli Wallach in his last film role.The film happens in New York City, 23 years after the first, and spins around the 2008 monetary emergency. Its plot focuses on an apparently changed Gordon Gekko, played by Douglas, and follows his endeavors to fix his relationship with his girl Winnie (Mulligan), with the assistance of her life partner, Jacob Moore (LaBeouf).Principal photography occurred in New York City among September and November 2009. In the wake of having its delivery date moved twice, Money Never Sleeps was delivered dramatically worldwide on September 24, 2010, by twentieth Century Fox. Preceding its official delivery, numerous writers associated with the monetary business were supposedly demonstrated development screenings of the film. 
In spite of opening to positive gathering at the 2010 Cannes Film Festival, Money Never Sleeps got blended surveys from pundits. In spite of the fact that neglecting to live up to its basic desires, the film was effective in the cinema world, besting the United States’ positioning during its initial end of the week, and procuring an overall complete of $134 million in ticket deals, and more than $15 million on DVD.
